{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486934"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"211"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/211"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.07,0.25,0.01,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"211"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/211"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"211"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93220"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"182"},{"type":"tags","id":"2169"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45147"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is planned for a gastric resection in two weeks time of a recently diagnosed carcinoma of the stomach. He has a medical history of a spontaneous deep vein thrombosis occurring nine months ago. His medications include rivaroxaban 20mg daily. His haematological and serum biochemical investigations do not show any abnormalities. He weighs 82kg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With regard to his anticoagulant status, which one of the following management plans is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease three days prior to surgery and start bridging therapy","Cease on morning of surgery","Cease two days prior to surgery","Delay surgery for one month","Cease on morning of surgery and start bridging therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a patient who has had an episode of venous thromboembolism (VTE) the chance of recurrence can be as high as 40% and ideally any elective surgery should be delayed for at least three months after the episode (i.e. \u003Cstrong\u003Edelayed for one month in this case)\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst it would be appropriate to delay non-urgent surgery to allow for completion of a post-thrombosis treatment regimen, such delay would not be appropriate in this case as delaying surgery significantly risks progression of his malignancy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe planned surgical procedure has a high risk of bleeding and stopping the rivaroxaban prior to the operation will be necessary. Rivaroxaban has a half-life of 5-9 hours in young people and 11-13 hours in older people. On the provided information that his biochemical investigations are normal, therefore the patient\u0027s renal function is normal, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecessation two days prior to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E will allow sufficient time for clearance of rivaroxaban from the patient\u0027s bloodstream to reduce any operative bleeding risk. Coupled with the fact that maximum plasma concentrations are reached 2-4 hours after tablet intake, this medication can be stopped and started close enough to the surgery such that the period without anticoagulation is brief enough \u003Cstrong\u003Enot to require bridging therapy.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInterrupting anticoagulation for surgery does not always need bridging therapy. Mechanical heart valves always need bridging therapy due to high stroke risk. Atrial fibrillation with a recent stroke or CHADS-VASc score \u0026gt;4, high-risk thrombophilic conditions, or a venous thromboembolic event within the last 4 weeks are conditions that should be considered for bridging therapy but the duration of interruption, patient comorbidities and the bleeding risk of the procedure will also contribute to the final anticoagulation plan. Patients with atrial fibrillation and CHADS-VASc score 4 or less, or those with a venous thromboembolic event \u0026gt;4 weeks ago do not routinely require bridging anticoagulation, especially if using DOACs which have a shorter period of cessation compared to Warfarin. Patients who had a venous thromboembolic episode 8-12 weeks previously are still at increased risk of recurrence during anticoagulation interruption so bridging therapy may be considered but is not mandated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cessation of rivaroxaban prior to a surgical procedure does not routinely require bridging therapy."],"references":["Guidelines on Periprocedural Management of Anticoagulant and Antiplatelet Agents Version 2.0. In: Clinical Excellence Commission, NSW Health [online]. 2025 [cited 2025 Aug 8]. Available at: https://www.cec.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/458988/Guidelines-on-perioperative-management-of-anticoagulant-and-antiplatelet-agents.pdf","Mueck W, Stampfuss J, Kubitza D, Beck M. Clinical Pharmacokinetic and Pharmacodynamic Profile of Rivaroxaban. Clin Pharmacokinet. 2014;53:1-16. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3889701/","Hornor MA, Duane TM, Ehlers AP, et al. American College of Surgeons\u0027 Guidelines for the Perioperative Management of Antithrombotic Medication. J Am Coll Surg. 2018; 227:521-36. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30145286/","Douketis JD, Spyropoulos AC, Kaatz S, Becker RC, Caprini JA, Dunn AS, Garcia DA, Jacobson A, Jaffer AK, Kong DF, Schulman S, Turpie AG, Hasselblad V, Ortel TL; BRIDGE Investigators. Perioperative Bridging Anticoagulation in Patients with Atrial Fibrillation. N Engl J Med. 2015 Aug 27;373(9):823-33"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93220"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"211"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93220"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T20:19:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-08T20:21:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"211"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emed